
[1]calk

   CALK, v.t. cauk.

   1. To drive oakum or old ropes untwised, into the seams of a ship or
   other vessel, to prevent their leaking, or admitting water. After the
   seams are filled, they are covered with hot melted pitch or rosin, to
   keep the oakum from rotting.

   2. In some parts of America, to set upon a horse or ox shoes armed with
   sharp points of iron, to prevent their slipping on ice; that is, to
   stop from slipping.

   CALK, n. Cauk. In New-England, a sharp pointed piece of iron on a shoe
   for a horse or an ox, called in Great Britain calking; used to prevent
                          the animal from slipping.
